<h1>Corporate Governance</h1>

<p>Effective governance isn't just for large corporations. Startups, LLCs, and small businesses need clear governance structures from the beginning — and the cost of neglecting them rarely appears until the worst possible moment: a fundraising round, an acquisition, or a dispute between founders.</p>

<p>At VMG Business Advisory, I provide practical corporate governance counsel designed for the realities of small and growing companies. The goal is a structure that actually fits how your business operates, not one that creates overhead for its own sake.</p>

<h2>What I Help With</h2>

<h3>Board and Management Structure</h3>
<p>Drafting and advising on operating agreements, bylaws, board resolutions, and written consents that establish clear, enforceable decision-making authority. This includes structuring advisory boards, board committees, and management roles in a way that reflects how the company is actually run and where it is headed.</p>

<h3>Founder and Shareholder Agreements</h3>
<p>Drafting and negotiating shareholder agreements, voting agreements, and buy-sell arrangements that protect each party's interests and establish a clear framework for major decisions, equity transfers, and dispute resolution. These agreements are always easier to negotiate before a dispute than during one — getting them in place early is one of the highest-value things a founding team can do.</p>

<h3>Fiduciary Duties and Director Responsibilities</h3>
<p>Advising directors, officers, and managers on their duties — including the duty of care and duty of loyalty — and helping companies implement internal policies and procedures that support informed decision-making and reduce liability exposure.</p>

<h3>Governance Cleanup Before a Transaction</h3>
<p>Many startups operate for years with informal governance and incomplete records. Investors and acquirers conduct detailed diligence that regularly surfaces these gaps and creates friction or delay in closings. I help companies audit their governance posture and address deficiencies before they become deal blockers.</p>

<h2>Who This Is For</h2>

<p>My corporate governance clients include tech startups, professional service firms, nonprofits, and established small businesses across a range of industries. Whether you are forming a new entity, restructuring after a period of growth, or preparing for a financing event, sound governance is a foundational part of long-term business value — and something a solo practitioner with startup experience can deliver without large-firm overhead.</p>

